In the proof of `vec_set_map`, we use `funext i` to consider an arbitrary index `i`. Then we use `fin_cases i` to split into two cases: `i = ↑idx` and `i ≠ ↑idx`.

In the case `i = ↑idx`:
- The left side is `((v.set (↑idx) elt).mapFinIdx f) ↑idx`. By the definition of `mapFinIdx`, this is `f ↑idx (v[(↑idx : Nat)]).get ...`. Since we're setting the element at `↑idx`, `v[(↑idx : Nat)]` is `elt`. So this becomes `f ↑idx (elt)`.
- The right side is `((v.mapFinIdx f).set (↑idx) (f (↑idx) elt ⋯)) ↑idx`. By the definition of `set`, this is `f (↑idx) elt ⋯`.
- We need to show `f ↑idx (elt) = f (↑idx) elt ⋯`. This is true by reflexivity of equality.

In the case `i ≠ ↑idx`:
- The left side is `((v.set (↑idx) elt).mapFinIdx f) i`. Since `i ≠ ↑idx`, the element `v[i]` is unchanged. So this is `f i (v[i])`.
- The right side is `((v.mapFinIdx f).set (↑idx) (f (↑idx) elt ⋯)) i`. Since `i ≠ ↑idx`, the element `v[i]` is unchanged. So this is `f i (v[i])`.
- We need to show `f i (v[i]) = f i (v[i])`. This is true by reflexivity of equality.

The `simp` tactic with `f` and `v` should handle these calculations. The `try { tauto }` and `try { aesop }` are fallbacks to close any trivial goals that might remain.
